<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-09-28T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-09-28T04:00:00-05:00" n="885" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d885">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense (M)/391:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Turkey</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Kelley</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Istanbul</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-09-28T12:00:00+03:00">September 28, 1940—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 3:05
                                    p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>107. My 158, September 25, 6 p.m. The Secretary General of the
                                Foreign Office informed me this morning that the Turkish Government
                                is pleased to comply with our request and has already granted to the
                                British Government the desired permission with regard to the sale of
                                chrome to us. He said that the Government had decided that it was
                                more feasible to arrange for our purchase of Turkish chrome through
                                Great Britain than through a direct transaction between the Turkish
                                Government and the United States. The Turkish Ambassador in
                                Washington has been advised of the Turkish Government’s action in
                                this matter.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Kelley</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>